apsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-09|2|82|373|||373|+9.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-10|2|93|407|||407|+9.1%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-11|2|95|428|||428|+5.2%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-12|2|97|445|||445|+4.0%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Row|2020-04-13|3|101|473|||473|+6.3%|divisor=1.8|numwidth=tw|collapsible=y}}\n\n|caption='''Source:'''<ref name=\"coronavirus/#cases\">{{cite web|url=https://novascotia.ca/coronavirus/#cases |title=Novel coronavirus (COVID-19): COVID-19 testing data |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\nOn March 15, Nova Scotia's first three presumptive cases were detected, all travel-related. Respectively, these cases were a woman in her 60s from [[Kings County, Nova Scotia|Kings County]] who visited [[Australia]] and returned March 8, a man in his late 50s from the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] area who attended a conference in [[California]] and returned March 13, and a man in his 30s from the [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] area who travelled \"throughout Europe\" and returned March 10.<ref name=\"novascotia2\"/>\n\nOn March 16, two additional cases were reported. A man and a woman in their 50s from the [[Halifax Regional Municipality]] had not traveled, but had been in \"close contact with individuals who had recently travelled outside the country.\"<ref name=\"novascotia3\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200316001 |title=Two New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Chief Medical Officer of Health Dr. Robert Strang announced that the reporting of information about individual cases would cease in order to protect patient privacy, as well as to prevent a false sense of security in communities without detected cases.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: N.S. limits public gatherings to 50 people as case numbers grow|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6689497/tuesday-coronavirus-update/|last=Benjamin|first=Graeme|date=March 17, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322191330/https://globalnews.ca/news/6689497/tuesday-coronavirus-update/|archive-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"novascotia4\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317001 |title=New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, a provincial state of emergency was declared. It was also announced that the [[QEII Health Sciences Center|QEII Health Sciences Centre's Microbiology Lab]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] was certified to report positive and negative tests for COVID-19, thus cases could be confirmed within the province, without needing to send samples to the [[National Microbiology Laboratory|National Microbiology Lab]] for confirmation.<ref name=\"novascotia5\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200322001 |title=State of Emergency Declared in Response to COVID-19, Seven New Cases |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151542/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200322001 |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, it was reported that at least one of the new cases was a child under age 10.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Nova Scotia now has 41 cases, including at least one child under 10|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6717912/13-new-cases-ns/|last=Benjamin|first=Graeme|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Chief Medical Officer of Health Dr. Robert Strang announced the first official case of community spread, per the government definition of a case that can not be connected to travel or a previously known case.<ref name=\"novascotia6\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200330003 |title=Five New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was reported that cases had been identified in four staff members and two residents of long-term care facilities for seniors.<ref name=\"novascotia7\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200331001 |title=Twenty New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-31 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, the province reported its first death, a [[Cape Breton]] woman in her 70s with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cape Breton woman in her 70s is Nova Scotia's first death related to COVID-19 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/covid-19-death-nova-scotia-1.5524447 |website=CBC.ca |publisher=CBC News |date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, the province reported its second death, a [[Cape Breton]] woman in her 90s with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second death related to COVID-19 confirmed in Nova Scotia|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/second-covid-19-death-1.5527637|website=CBC.ca |publisher=CBC News |date=April 9, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\nOn February 28, the Nova Scotia Human Rights Commission issued a press release in which Nova Scotians were \"asked to be vigilant against discrimination based on ethnic or national origin\" and cautioned that the \"Nova Scotia Human Rights Act protects against discrimination based on an irrational fear of contracting an illness or disease.\"<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200228007 |title= COVID-19 and Discrimination |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231557/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200228007 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, Nova Scotia school trips to international destinations were cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200304005 |title=School Organized Trips to International Destinations Cancelled |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-04 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, the provincial government announced that preparations for the virus were \"well underway,\" including the implementation of a patient screening process for healthcare workers, monitoring and investigation of potential cases, application of public health and infection control measures, and work with the Nova Scotia's Emergency Management Office.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200306003 |title=Coronavirus Preparations Well Underway |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, new national screening protocols were implemented in which those who had travelled outside Canada were requested to monitor for symptoms for 14 days, and those who began to feel unwell were requested to stay home and self-isolate from the public. Those who developed a fever of 38&nbsp;\u00b0C or higher and/or cough were requested to contact the health information line at 811 for assessment. Hygiene directives in regards to proper handwashing and cough etiquette were also issued.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200309002 |title=New National Screening Protocols for COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, all Nova Scotia public sector employees who travelled outside Canada were required to self-isolate for 14 days upon return.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313002 |title=New Travel Measures for Nova Scotia Public Sector Employees |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318085459/https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313002 |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, Nova Scotia museums and art galleries were closed.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200313009 |title=Nova Scotia Museum Sites, Art Gallery of Nova Scotia Closed |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-13 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the Shubenacadie Wildlife Park was closed.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200314001 |title=Shubenacadie Wildlife Park to Close |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-14 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, Nova Scotia correctional facilities were closed to volunteer organizations, and inmates were limited to non-contact visitation by family and friends, meaning separation by a pane of glass and communication via a phone line. Inmates were also granted two free phone calls per week. There was no change in protocol for visitation by lawyers.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200314002 |title=Changes to Correctional Facilities Visits to Prevent COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-14 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, provincial visitor information centres for tourists were closed, and the call centre responsible for fielding inquiries from tourists was also shuttered.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315001 |title=Provincial Visitor Information Centres to Close Until Further Notice |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-15 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, long-term care facilities were closed to visitors, public schools were shut for two weeks from March 23 following March Break (subject to reassessment and extension), day cares were closed, March Break camps were cancelled, casinos were closed, bar owners were no longer allowed to operate video lottery terminals (VLTs), everyone who travelled outside Canada was asked to self-isolate regardless of the development of symptoms, social distancing of two metres was recommended, and gatherings were restricted to 150 \"or much smaller if possible.\"<ref name=\"novascotia2\"/> Further, all visitation to correctional facilities was suspended and lawyers were asked to arrange alternative means of maintaining contact with clients. Inmates were granted extra phone calls. Correctional Services also closed its facilities to all visitors until further notice.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200315004 |title=All Visits to Correctional Facilities Suspended to Prevent COVID-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-15 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Nova Scotians were directed to first complete an online screening questionnaire before calling the 811 hotline due to an overwhelming influx of calls.<ref name=\"novascotia3\"/> Additionally, the government of Nova Scotia issued a warning about ongoing investment scams, with individuals impersonating banks over the phone.<ref>{{cite press release|author=Stephanie Atkinson |url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200316003 |title=Warning About COVID-19 Investment Scams |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Access Nova Scotia and offices of the Registry of Motor Vehicles were closed. Driver licences and vehicle registrations expiring in March, April and May were extended to August 31.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317003 |title=Closure of Access Nova Scotia and Registry of Motor Vehicle Offices, Deadline Extension |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, bars were ordered closed, restaurants were limited to take-out and delivery only, and public gatherings were limited to 50 or fewer.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200317005 |title=Province\u2019s Bars to Close, Restaurants Limited to Take-out, Delivery as of Thursday; Gatherings Limited to 50 or Fewer Effective Immediately |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, a number of new measures were announced to combat the spread of the virus. Doctors and pharmacists were granted expanded options for virtual care using telephone and video conference, pharmacists were allowed to renew prescriptions for most medications, employers were no longer allowed to require a doctor's note from employees seeking to take time off work, nurses were called from retirement to staff the 811 hotline, and service providers funded through the Department of Community Services\u2019 Disability Support Program were shuttered. A number of other services such as barber shops, tattoo shops, nail salons, and gyms were also ordered closed effective midnight March 19.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200318004 |title=New Restrictions; Province, Health System Working to Increase Capacity |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-18 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Additionally, 41 inmates serving intermittent sentences in four adult correctional facilities were released on temporary absence.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200318003 |title=Correctional Facilities Take Further Acton to Prevent Covid-19 |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-18 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Premier Stephen McNeil announced the allocation of $2.2 million for an increase of $50 to every individual and family member on income assistance, $1 million to the Feed Nova Scotia food bank, a three-month suspension of evictions, emergency funding of $230,000 for Senior Safety Programs and Community Links, as well as an order for university students still living in residence to go home, and for those university students unable to return home to practice social distancing.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200319004 |title=Measures to Help Vulnerable Nova Scotians |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-19 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the provincial government announced an allocation of $161 million for cash flow and credit access for small and medium Nova Scotia businesses. Payments on many government loans to businesses were deferred until June 30, and payments on Nova Scotia student loans were suspended until September 30. The government also allocated $15 million as an incentive for internet service providers to expand internet infrastructure.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200320003 |title=Measures to Help Nova Scotia Businesses, Students |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-20 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, a number of health measures were announced, including the restriction of visitors to hospitals and the opening of new assessment centres, of which there 14 at the time.<ref name=\"novascotia8\">{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200321001 |title=Six New Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-21 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the province of Nova Scotia declared a state of emergency. In accordance with the emergency declaration, land sea, and air points of entry were tightened, with anyone entering the province stopped, questioned, and told to self-isolate for 14 days, starting March 23. All provincial parks, beaches, and tourist attractions were closed, although provincial trails were left open for exercise. Police were authorized to enforce orders under the Health Protection Act, as well as the Emergency Management Act. Gatherings over 5 people were prohibited. Non-essential businesses were only allowed to remain open as long as a two-metre distance can be maintained. Dentists were no longer allowed to practice in their offices except in emergency circumstances.<ref name=\"novascotia5\"/>\n\nOn March 24, a series of new public health measures were announced, including the testing of all close contacts of positive cases, doubled lab capacity for viral testing, increased capacity for the 811 hotline, enhancement of infectious disease control measures in hospitals, restriction of regulated health professions to virtual care except for emergency or urgent cases, all non-regulated health professions closed, and the reopening of Access Nova Scotia Centres and Registry of Motor Vehicle Offices on a limited, reduced contact basis. Economic sectors deemed essential services and therefore exempt from gathering limitations were defined.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200324003 |title=Strengthening Health System and New Measures |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, qualifying criteria for viral testing was expanded beyond travel-related cases to include anyone referred to an assessment centre by the 811 system, all close contacts of confirmed cases, and people in hospital who meet testing criteria. An alternative hotline for sick medical staff was also established in response to an overburdened 811 system. Additionally, camping reservations were put on hold and open fires were banned within 305 metres of woods throughout the province.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200326003 |title=Testing for COVID-19 Expands; Health System Preparations |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, a Halifax woman was fined $697.50, and had her vehicle seized by police after she was found in a park despite Nova Scotia having closed parks and beaches to the public under its emergency measures act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6748452/halifax-police-issue-ticket-covid-19-emergency-order/|title=Halifax police seize vehicle, issue ticket to woman violating COVID-19 emergency order|publisher=globalnews.ca|date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the provincial government released a more comprehensive plan for how schools will proceed through the coronavirus pandemic, as well as an online tool for businesses.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200330004 |title=Plan for At-home Student Learning, Online Guidance for Business |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, the provincial government announced that a map will be released in the near future online showing where cases are located across the province organized by the four health zones.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benjamin |first1=Graeme |title=Breakdown of where coronavirus cases are in Nova Scotia coming soon: Strang |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6755757/20-new-cases-in-nova-scotia/ |website=globalnews.ca |publisher=Global News |date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, the province of Nova Scotia renewed the declaration of a state of emergency extending the previous until April 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://novascotia.ca/coronavirus/Direction-of-the-Minister-under-a-Declared-State-of-Emergency.pdf|title=Renewal of Provincial State of Emergency by Minister|last=|first=|date=|website=novascotia.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, it was announced that travel was no longer a prerequisite for testing, as community spread had reached levels that anyone could potentially have the virus regardless of travel history.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200406004|title=Measures to Further Help Prevent Spread of COVID-19|publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada|date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-06|url-status=live|website=Novascotia.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Schools and universities ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nIn March, all Nova Scotian universities suspended in-person classes and restricted access to their campuses. Many transitioned to a distance learning model for the remainder of the academic term.<ref>{{Cite news|title=How Nova Scotia universities are dealing with the COVID-19 pandemic|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/in-person-classes-at-dal-king-s-suspended-next-week-1.5497273|last=Patil|first=Anjuli|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=CBC News}}</ref>\n\n== Economic impact ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nIn February, Nova Scotia's billion dollar lobster industry was negatively impacted by coronavirus, with a large portion of exports previously going to China. Lobster exports became difficult as air cargo carriers began to suspend service. Lobster prices dropped with a glut in the local market due to restricted exports.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nova Scotia\u2019s lobster industry fears prolonged effects of coronavirus outbreak as exports halted, prices drop|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotias-lobster-industry-fears-prolonged-effects-of-coronavirus/|last=Mercer|first=Greg|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn March, a number of Nova Scotia distilleries shifted production from alcoholic beverages to alcohol-based hand sanitizers.<ref>{{Cite news|title=These Nova Scotia distilleries are producing hand sanitizer in time of need|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/these-nova-scotia-distilleries-are-producing-hand-sanitizer-in-time-of-need-1.4858050|last=April|first=Allan|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=CTV News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a survey published by Restaurants Canada on April 2, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|first=Marlee |last=Wasser |url=https://www.restaurantscanada.org/industry-news/covid-19-has-cost-the-foodservice-sector-800000-jobs-since-march-1/ |title=COVID-19 has cost the foodservice sector 800,000 jobs since March 1 |website=Restaurants Canada |date=2020-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> approximately 24,500 Nova Scotian restaurant workers have lost their jobs. Staff have been laid off at about four out of five Nova Scotia restaurants since the beginning of March, around one tenth of restaurants have permanently closed, and a further 18 percent expect to close within a month if nothing changes. Some restaurants have been able to pivot to a take-out or delivery only business model in order to maintain cash flow amid mandatory closures of dining areas.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coronavirus: Amid record job losses, Nova Scotia restaurant owners innovate|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6767133/record-job-losses-ns-restaurants-innovate/|last=McSheffrey|first=Elizabeth|date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020|url-status=live|work=Global News}}</ref>\n\n== Data ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in Nova Scotia\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Date\n! colspan=\"3\" |Presumptive\n! colspan=\"2\" |Confirmed\n! colspan=\"2\" |Deaths\n! colspan=\"2\" |Recoveries\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|HC|Hospitalized cases}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|NT|Negative tests}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|TT|Total tests}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|Tests<br>per k|Total tests per thousand inhabitants}} \n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{abbr|Cases<br>per m|Total cases per million inhabitants}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Sources\n|-\n!New\n!{{abbr|PCC|Presumptive cases confirmed}}\n!{{abbr|Cml|Cumulative}}\n!New\n!{{abbr|Cml|Cumulative}}\n!New\n!{{abbr|Cml|Cumulative}}\n!New\n!{{abbr|Cml|Cumulative}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 15|March 15, 2020}}\n|3\n|\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|415\n|418\n|0.4\n|3.1\n|<ref name=\"novascotia2\"/>\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 16|March 16, 2020}}\n|2\n|\n|5\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|671\n|676\n|0.7\n|5.1\n|<ref name=\"novascotia3\"/>\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 17|March 17, 2020}}\n|2\n|1\n|7\n|1\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|934\n|942\n|0.9\n|7.2\n|<ref name=\"novascotia4\"/>\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 18|March 18, 2020}}\n|5\n|2\n|9\n|2\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|1,141\n|1,153\n|1.2\n|12.3\n|<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200318001 |title=Five New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-18 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 19|March 19, 2020}}\n|2\n|2\n|9\n|2\n|5\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|1,373\n|1,387\n|1.4\n|14.3\n|<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://novascotia.ca/news/release/?id=20200319003 |title=Two New Presumptive Cases of COVID-19 in Nova Scotia |publisher=Government of Nova Scotia, Canada |website=Novascotia.ca |date=2020-03-19 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n|-\n!{{abbr|Mar 20|March 20, 2020}}\n|1\n|\n|10\n|\n|5\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|1,546\n|1,561\n|1.6\n|15.3\n|<ref>{{