stern Ghats]], while along the west, it is bordered by the [[Laccadive Sea]].\n\nThe district, covering an area of around 1992&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, has a population (2011 [[census]]) of 1,307,375. It has four [[taluk]]s, namely, [[Kasaragod taluk|Kasaragod]], [[Hosdurg taluk|Hosdurg]], [[Vellarikundu]] and [[Manjeshwaram Taluk]]. \n\nIt has three municipalities: [[Kasaragod]], [[Kanhangad]], [[Nileshwaram]] and 38 [[Gram panchayat]]s.<ref>[http://www.kasargod.nic.in/administration/pangrama.htm There are 38 Grama Panchayats in Kasaragod District] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006142922/http://kasargod.nic.in/administration/pangrama.htm |date=6 October 2014 }} (kasaragod.nic.in).</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main article|History of Kasaragod}}\nKasaragod was known to the [[Arabs]] by the name ''Harkwillia''.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ksd.kerala.gov.in/hist.htm |title=Kasaragod History |publisher=Government of Kerala |accessdate=2009-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925134038/http://www.ksd.kerala.gov.in/hist.htm |archivedate=25 September 2008 }}</ref>\nMany Arab travelers who visited Kerala between the 9th and the 14th centuries visited Kasaragod, which was an important trade centre then. ''Duarte Borbosa'', the Portuguese traveler who visited [[Kumbla]], near [[Kasaragod Town|Kasaragod]] in 1514, recorded rice being exported for coir to [[Maldives]].<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nKasaragod was part of the kumbala Kingdom in which there were 64 [[Malayalam]] and [[Tulu people|Tulu]]  villages.<ref name=\"history\" />\nWhen the [[Vijayanagara empire]] attacked Kasaragod, it was still under the [[Kolathiri]] [[Raja]] who had Nileshwaram as one of his capitals. During the decline of the Vijayanagara empire, the administration of this area was vested with [[Nayakas of Keladi|Ikkeri Nayakas]].<ref name=\"history\" /> At the onset of collapse of the Vijayanagara empire, ''Venkappa Nayaka'' declared independence to Ikkery. Kumbla, Chandragiri and Bekal are considered to be the chain of forts constructed or renovated by [[Shivappa Nayaka]].<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nFrancis Buccanan, the family doctor of [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Arthur Wellesley]], visited Kasargod in 1800.<ref name=\"history\" /> In his travelogue, he recorded information on places like Athiraparambu, Kavvai, [[Nileshwaram]], [[Bekal]], [[Chandragiri]] and [[Manjeshwar]].<ref name=\"history\" /> Hosdurg and Vellarikundu is part of Kolathunadu  (south of Chandragiri river) and Kasaragod and Manjeshwaram is in the Tulunadu region (north of Chandragiri river).\nIn 1763, [[Hyder Ali]] conquered Bedanoor (Bidnur), the capital of the Ikkery Naiks. His son [[Tippu Sultan]] conquered much of [[Malabar (Northern Kerala)|Malabar]]. As per the ''Sreerangapattanam Treaty'' of 1792, Tippu surrendered Malabar, except [[Kanara]] to the [[British India|British]]. The British occupied Kanara only after the death of Tippu Sultan.<ref name=\"history\" /> it is said that ''Kinavoor Molom'' (Sree Dharma Shashtha Temple)is belonging to ''Karinthalam'' (one of 64 Brahmin villages in old Kerala).\n\nBefore the formation of Kerala, Kasaragod was a part of [[South Canara]] district of erstwhile [[Madras Presidency]]. Kasaragod became part of [[Kannur district]] following the reorganisation of states and formation of Kerala in 1 November 1956.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://kasargod.nic.in/profile/afterdisform.htm |title= Kasaragod - After District Formation |publisher= Kasaragod District |accessdate= 2009-03-11 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090410025049/http://kasargod.nic.in/profile/afterdisform.htm |archive-date= 10 April 2009 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Kasaragod was declared a district in the year 1984. Merger of Kasargod with Kerala has been a contentious issue as there is a sizeable population which speaks Kannada and Tulu which are the languages of Karnataka. Government of India formed the Mahajan Commission on 25 October 1966 to look into the issue along with a similar issue Karnataka had with Maharashtra over Belagaavi district. The commission was headed by the third Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of India, Meher Chand Mahajan. The commission recommended that the part of the district that is to the north of Chandragiri river, which includes the Kasargod town, should be merged with Karnataka.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe district is the northernmost district of the State of Kerala. Kasaragod is located at {{coord|12.5|N|75.0|E|}}.<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/13/Kasaragod.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Kasaragod]</ref> It has an average elevation of 19&nbsp; metres (62&nbsp; feet).\n[[Ranipuram]] or Madathumala (1016m) peak is the highest peak in the Kasargod district of Kerala. It is located in the Ranipuram Wildlife Sanctuary.\n\n== Climate ==\n{{Weather box\n|location = Kasaragod\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 33.1\n|Feb high C = 33.3\n|Mar high C = 33.9\n|Apr high C = 34.3\n|May high C = 33.4\n|Jun high C = 29.8\n|Jul high C = 28.7\n|Aug high C = 28.8\n|Sep high C = 30.1\n|Oct high C = 31.2\n|Nov high C = 32.7\n|Dec high C = 33.1\n|Jan low C = 21.1\n|Feb low C = 21.9\n|Mar low C = 23.7\n|Apr low C = 24.9\n|May low C = 24.9\n|Jun low C = 23.5\n|Jul low C = 23\n|Aug low C = 23\n|Sep low C = 23.2\n|Oct low C = 23.2\n|Nov low C = 22.7\n|Dec low C = 21.3\n|Jan precipitation mm = 0.8\n|Feb precipitation mm = 0\n|Mar precipitation mm = 17.3\n|Apr precipitation mm = 32.7\n|May precipitation mm = 182.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 1010.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 1002.8\n|Aug precipitation mm = 663.6\n|Sep precipitation mm = 246.5\n|Oct precipitation mm = 222.6\n|Nov precipitation mm = 69\n|Dec precipitation mm = 12.4\n|source = [http://www.meoweather.com/history/India/na/12.5/75/Kasaragod.html?# Meo Weather]\n|date=May 2012}}\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Kasaragod District\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|56.8}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|37.2}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians|Christian]]|blue|6.7}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|0.3}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n<small>Source: 2011 Census.</small>\n}}\n[[File:Kasaragod-map-en.svg|thumb|267px|Kasaragod District Map]]\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Kasaragod district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 1,307,375,<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 2011-09-30 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> roughly equal to the nation of [[Mauritius]]<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 2011-10-01 | quote =\nMauritius 1,303,717 July 2011 est.\n}}</ref> or the US state of [[New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php\n |title=2010 Resident Population Data\n |publisher=U. S. Census Bureau\n |accessdate=2011-09-30\n |quote=New Hampshire 1,316,470\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101090833/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php\n |archivedate=1 January 2011\n}}</ref> This gives it a ranking of 375th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus/> The district has a population density of {{convert| 654 |PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}} .<ref name=districtcensus/> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001\u20132011 was 8.18%.<ref name=districtcensus/> Kasaragod has a [[sex ratio]] of 1079 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus/> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 89.85%.<ref name=districtcensus/>\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=2,31,280|13=1911|14=2,47,467|15=1921|16=2,56,931|17=1931|18=3,02,043|19=1941|20=3,42,301|21=1951|22=4,11,031|23=1961|24=5,12,146|25=1971|26=6,83,020|27=1981|28=8,72,741|29=1991|30=10,71,508|31=2001|32=12,04,078|33=2011|34=13,07,375|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=middle}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kasaragod East]]\n* [[Kasaragod North]]\n* [[Kasaragod taluk]]\n* [[Kuniyan River]]\n* [[List of educational institutions in Kasaragod district]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Kasaragod district}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Kasaragod District}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190616163313/http://www.kasargod.nic.in/ Official District Website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles Related to Kasaragod district\n| list =\n{{Kasaragod district}}\n{{Kasaragod District Municipalities}}\n{{North Malabar}}\n{{Places of interest in North Malabar}}\n}}\n{{Districts of Kerala}}\n{{Kerala}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kasaragod District}}\n[[Category:Kasaragod district| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n[[Category:Districts of Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4073:2015:8bcc:c973:5199:30d:dd1e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kasaragod_district"}
{"title_page": "Ilomilo (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 single by Billie Eilish}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Ilomilo\n| cover      = [[File:Ilomilobillieeilish.PNG|200px]]\n| caption    = Spotify cover \n| alt        = \n| type       = single\n| cover_size = \n| artist     = [[Billie Eilish]]\n| album      = [[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]\n| released   = {{start date|2019|03|29}}\n| recorded   = \n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre      = <!--Please source genres -->\n| length     = 2:36\n| label      =\n* Darkroom\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Billie Eilish|Billie Eilish O'Connell]]\n* [[Finneas O'Connell]]\n| producer   = Finneas O'Connell\n| prev_title = [[No Time to Die (Billie Eilish song)|No Time to Die]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''Ilomilo'''\" (stylized in [[lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song by American singer [[Billie Eilish]] from her debut studio album ''[[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]''. It was written by Eilish and her brother Finneas O'Connell, who also produced the song. The song peaked at number 62 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2019-04-13 |title=Billboard |website= Billboard |publisher= Billboard|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> and charted in the top 100 in multiple countries. It was also certified gold in Australia, Canada, and the United States.\n\nIt is preceded by \"[[Bury a Friend]]\" on its parent album, and the beginning instrumental of \"Ilomilo\" is featured at the end of its preceding track. The song impacted contemporary hit radio in Italy on April 10, 2020. But was actually released on March 29.<ref name = radio>{{Cite web|url=http://radiodate.it/radio-date/billie-eilish-ilomilo-200412-10-04-2020-radiodate/|title=BILLIE EILISH \"ilomilo\" {{!}} (Radio Date: 10/04/2020)|website=radiodate.it|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe song was inspired by the computer game [[ilomilo]], which is a 2010 puzzle game where the goal is to reunite two characters named \"Ilo\" and \"Milo\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The song was also partially inspired by the novel and film ''Bridge to Terabithia''.<ref>https://twitter.com/eilishupdates/status/1159608493453824001</ref> Eilish states: \"I used to play ilomilo a lot. I loved ilomilo, that was like my favorite game in the world. It's this game where it's these two little creatures \u2013 one is named ilo and the other's named milo. It's this sort of anti-gravity world where there's all these little blocks and they start apart from each other. The idea is you just get to each other and when they get to each other they just hug, there's no prize.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Prance|first=Sam|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/music/news/billie-eilish-ilomilo-lyrics-meaning/|title=Billie Eilish reveals the adorable story and meaning behind her 'ilomilo' lyrics|work=PopBuzz|date=March 29, 2019|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn an Interview with ''MTV'', Finneas states that \"I like songs that exist with the knowledge of other songs. They're not linked in that they need each other to exist, necessarily, but they're like two different episodes of the same TV show. Just little fun things like bleeding songs into each other, those make it feel like a full album.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nThe song is a mid tempo song  that is played in the key of [[C minor]], while Eilish's vocals span a range of G<sub>3</sub> to A<sub>b4</sub>. The first half is moderately fast at 120 beats per minute (BPM). The genre of the song was Alternative Pop/Rock and Indie Pop<ref name=\"notes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0195182|title=Billie Eilish \"ilomilo\" Sheet Music|publisher=Musicnotes.com|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n\"Ilomilo\" is about a person being separated from someone they love dearly and are trying to find them again. In it, Billie sings lines like: \"I don't wanna be lonely\" and \"I can't lose another life\". She also appears to reference a failed relationship by adding: \"I just wanted to protect you, but now I'll never get to.\" The person is afraid that their loved one will depart and never return. The person believes that the love they share is incomparable to what he will find in the outside world. Ultimately the song finishes with the chorus, where the person has been realized they are alone and their loved one is gone. The person is unaware of their location and wonders if they'll ever return. The persons desire for their loved one to \u201ccome home\u201d is so strong that they don't even care if they are such under false pretenses. <ref>{{cite web|last=Prance|first=Sam|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/music/news/billie-eilish-ilomilo-lyrics-meaning/|title=Billie Eilish reveals the adorable story and meaning behind her 'ilomilo' lyrics|work=PopBuzz|date=March 29, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The song is introduced during the final seconds of \"Bury a Friend.\" There are lyrical reference to \"Bury a Friend\" in \"Ilomilo\": \"The friends I've had to bury, they keep me up at night\". Fans have speculated that the two songs are linked, but Finneas says the connection is more about making the album sound cohesive.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"Ilomilo\" was met with critical appraise. In 2020, Insider placed the song at number 13 on their ''Every Billie Eilish song, ranked'' list, with Libby Torres calling it \"a catchy, mid tempo song with insanely relatable lyrics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.insider.com/billie-eilish-songs-ranked-best-worst|title = Every Billie Eilish song, ranked|author = Callie Ahlgrim, Libby Torres and Claudia Willen|access-date = April 5, 2020|date = March 18, 2020|website = Insider}}</ref> ''Circa the Future'' called it \"an underrated song\" and that \"her delicate vocals shine in this stunning song\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://circathepresent.blog/every-billie-eilish-song-ranked/|title =Every Billie Eilish Song Ranked|author=none|access-date = April 5, 2020|website = Circa the future}}</ref> ''[[Stereogum]]''{{'s}} Chris DeVille called the song a \"skittering\" track and that the song seems to be grappling with her place in a world wrecked by tragedy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2037018/billie-eilish-album-review/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Billie Eilish's Time Is Now|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=July 14, 2019|author=DeVille, Chris|work=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nUpon the release of ''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?'', \"Ilomilo\" debuted at number 62 on the US ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] for a week during April of 2019. It also made the top 100 in multiple countries including: Australia, Canada, Germany, Sweden, and the Netherlands. It was also certified gold in Canada, Australia and the United States.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|23|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|38|artist=Billie Eilish|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|98|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|songid=1855057|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|63|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|63|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|62|artist=Billie Eilish|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|artist=Billie Eilish|title=ilomilo|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Ilomilo|artist=Billie Eilish|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2019|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Ilomilo|artist=Billie Eilish|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true}}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 29, 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| {{hlist|[[Darkroom]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n|<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=\u200eWHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP, WHERE DO WE GO? by Billie Eilish|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/when-we-all-fall-asleep-where-do-we-go/1450695723|volume=|pages=|publisher=[[Apple Music]]|language=en-us|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Italy\n| April 10, 2020\n| [[Contemporary hit radio]]\n| Universal\n| <ref name = \"radio\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Billie Eilish}}\n\n[[Category:Billie Eilish songs]]\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Finneas O'Connell]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Billie Eilish]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Finneas O'Connell]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 single by Billie Eilish}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Ilomilo\n| cover      = [[File:Ilomilobillieeilish.PNG|200px]]\n| caption    = Spotify cover \n| alt        = \n| type       = single\n| cover_size = \n| artist     = [[Billie Eilish]]\n| album      = [[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]\n| released   = {{start date|2020|04|10}}\n| recorded   = \n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| genre      = <!--Please source genres -->\n| length     = 2:36\n| label      =\n* Darkroom\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Billie Eilish|Billie Eilish O'Connell]]\n* [[Finneas O'Connell]]\n| producer   = Finneas O'Connell\n| prev_title = [[No Time to Die (Billie Eilish song)|No Time to Die]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\"'''Ilomilo'''\" (stylized in [[lowercase|all lowercase]]) is a song by American singer [[Billie Eilish]] from her debut studio album ''[[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]''. It was written by Eilish and her brother Finneas O'Connell, who also produced the song. The song peaked at number 62 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2019-04-13 |title=Billboard |website= Billboard |publisher= Billboard|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> and charted in the top 100 in multiple countries. It was also certified gold in Australia, Canada, and the United States.\n\nIt is preceded by \"[[Bury a Friend]]\" on its parent album, and the beginning instrumental of \"Ilomilo\" is featured at the end of its preceding track. The song impacted contemporary hit radio in Italy on April 10, 2020.<ref name = radio>{{Cite web|url=http://radiodate.it/radio-date/billie-eilish-ilomilo-200412-10-04-2020-radiodate/|title=BILLIE EILISH \"ilomilo\" {{!}} (Radio Date: 10/04/2020)|website=radiodate.it|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe song was inspired by the computer game [[ilomilo]], which is a 2010 puzzle game where the goal is to reunite two characters named \"Ilo\" and \"Milo\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The song was also partially inspired by the novel and film ''Bridge to Terabithia''.<ref>https://twitter.com/eilishupdates/status/1159608493453824001</ref> Eilish states: \"I used to play ilomilo a lot. I loved ilomilo, that was like my favorite game in the world. It's this game where it's these two little creatures \u2013 one is named ilo and the other's named milo. It's this sort of anti-gravity world where there's all these little blocks and they start apart from each other. The idea is you just get to each other and when they get to each other they just hug, there's no prize.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Prance|first=Sam|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/music/news/billie-eilish-ilomilo-lyrics-meaning/|title=Billie Eilish reveals the adorable story and meaning behind her 'ilomilo' lyrics|work=PopBuzz|date=March 29, 2019|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn an Interview with ''MTV'', Finneas states that \"I like songs that exist with the knowledge of other songs. They're not linked in that they need each other to exist, necessarily, but they're like two different episodes of the same TV show. Just little fun things like bleeding songs into each other, those make it feel like a full album.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nThe song is a mid tempo song  that is played in the key of [[C minor]], while Eilish's vocals span a range of G<sub>3</sub> to A<sub>b4</sub>. The first half is moderately fast at 120 beats per minute (BPM). The genre of the song was Alternative Pop/Rock and Indie Pop<ref name=\"notes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0195182|title=Billie Eilish \"ilomilo\" Sheet Music|publisher=Musicnotes.com|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> \n\n\"Ilomilo\" is about a person being separated from someone they love dearly and are trying to find them again. In it, Billie sings lines like: \"I don't wanna be lonely\" and \"I can't lose another life\". She also appears to reference a failed relationship by adding: \"I just wanted to protect you, but now I'll never get to.\" The person is afraid that their loved one will depart and never return. The person believes that the love they share is incomparable to what he will find in the outside world. Ultimately the song finishes with the chorus, where the person has been realized they are alone and their loved one is gone. The person is unaware of their location and wonders if they'll ever return. The persons desire for their loved one to \u201ccome home\u201d is so strong that they don't even care if they are such under false pretenses. <ref>{{cite web|last=Prance|first=Sam|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/music/news/billie-eilish-ilomilo-lyrics-meaning/|title=Billie Eilish reveals the adorable story and meaning behind her 'ilomilo' lyrics|work=PopBuzz|date=March 29, 2019|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The song is introduced during the final seconds of \"Bury a Friend.\" There are lyrical reference to \"Bury a Friend\" in \"Ilomilo\": \"The friends I've had to bury, they keep me up at night\". Fans have speculated that the two songs are linked, but Finneas says the connection is more about making the album sound cohesive.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth|first=Madeline|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3119965/finneas-oconnell-billie-eilish-album-breakdown/|title=BILLIE EILISH'S WHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP: A COMPLETE BREAKDOWN FROM FINNEAS O'CONNELL|work=[[MTV]]|date=April 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\"Ilomilo\" was met with critical appraise. In 2020, Insider placed the song at number 13 on their ''Every Billie Eilish song, ranked'' list, with Libby Torres calling it \"a catchy, mid tempo song with insanely relatable lyrics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.insider.com/billie-eilish-songs-ranked-best-worst|title = Every Billie Eilish song, ranked|author = Callie Ahlgrim, Libby Torres and Claudia Willen|access-date = April 5, 2020|date = March 18, 2020|website = Insider}}</ref> ''Circa the Future'' called it \"an underrated song\" and that \"her delicate vocals shine in this stunning song\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://circathepresent.blog/every-billie-eilish-song-ranked/|title =Every Billie Eilish Song Ranked|author=none|access-date = April 5, 2020|website = Circa the future}}</ref> ''[[Stereogum]]''{{'s}} Chris DeVille called the song a \"skittering\" track and that the song seems to be grappling with her place in a world wrecked by tragedy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2037018/billie-eilish-album-review/franchises/the-week-in-pop/|title=Billie Eilish's Time Is Now|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=July 14, 2019|author=DeVille, Chris|work=[[Stereogum]]}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nUpon the release of ''When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?'', \"Ilomilo\" debuted at number 62 on the US ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] for a week during April of 2019. It also made the top 100 in multiple countries including: Australia, Canada, Germany, Sweden, and the Netherlands. It was also certified gold in Canada, Australia and the United States.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|23|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|38|artist=Billie Eilish|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|98|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|songid=1855057|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|63|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|63|artist=Billie Eilish|song=Ilomilo|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|62|artist=Billie Eilish|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|artist=Billie Eilish|title=ilomilo|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Ilomilo|artist=Billie Eilish|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2019|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Ilomilo|artist=Billie Eilish|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=2019|certyear=2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true}}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| March 29, 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| {{hlist|[[Darkroom]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n|<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=\u200eWHEN WE ALL FALL ASLEEP, WHERE DO WE GO? by Billie Eilish|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/when-we-all-fall-asleep-where-do-we-go/1450695723|volume=|pages=|publisher=[[Apple Music]]|language